rick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Suffolk): from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Godebald</i>, <i>Godbaud</i>, a medieval French form of the ancient Germanic name <i>Godebald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gōd</i> ‘good’ or <i>god</i> ‘god’ + <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’."],"variants":[{"name":"Godbolt","meanings":["English (East Anglia): variant of   Godbold  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":30,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Godbold was born about 1425, in Dennington, Suffolk, England. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Rasted. He died before 14 December 1507, in his hometown."},"et":{"say 1425–before 14 December 1507":"umbes 1425–enne 14. detsembrit 1507","1425–1507":"1425–15